ts_fs_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":7933,"ei":7950,"sm":{"ts_un":false,"ts_un_i":true,"ts_it_i":false,"ts_fs_i":false,"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_fgc":"#000000","ts_fgc_i":true,"ts_it":true,"ts_bd_i":false,"ts_va_i":true,"ts_fs":16.0,"ts_ff":"Droid Serif","ts_bd":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":7951,"ei":8209,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#000000","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":true,"ts_it":true,"ts_fs":13.0,"ts_ff":"Droid Serif","ts_it_i":false,"ts_bgc":"#c5e1a5","ts_fs_i":false,"ts_bgc_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":8210,"ei":8215,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#424242","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":8216,"ei":8229,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":8240,"ei":8266,"sm":{"ts_un":false,"ts_un_i":true,"ts_it_i":false,"ts_fs_i":false,"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_fgc":"#000000","ts_fgc_i":true,"ts_it":true,"ts_bd_i":false,"ts_va_i":true,"ts_fs":16.0,"ts_ff":"Droid Serif","ts_bd":false}},{"ty":"as","st":"text","si":8267,"ei":8280,"sm":{"ts_ff_i":false,"ts_un":false,"ts_fgc":"#757575","ts_un_i":true,"ts_fgc_i":false,"ts_fs":11.0,"ts_ff":"Roboto","ts_fs_i":false}}]; DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart = new Date().getTime(); _getTimingInstance().incrementTime(, DOCS_modelChunkLoadStart - DOCS_modelChunkParseStart); DOCS_warmStartDocumentLoader.loadModelChunk(DOCS_modelChunk); DOCS_modelChunk = undefined;</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="zS0KkByA8cnoyim0re97dMRn57I"  nonce="zS0KkByA8cnoyim0re97dMRn57I">DOCS_modelChunkParseStart = new Date().getTime();</script><script type="text/javascript" nonce="zS0KkByA8cnoyim0re97dMRn57I"  nonce="zS0KkByA8cnoyim0re97dMRn57I">DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":8288,"s":"\n\n\nYour Faith, My Faith\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cMay your god and our god bless you”—and whose god was blessing whom—had gone from funny to controversial to confrontational. I found myself keeping quiet. Almost hiding. I think many people in minority religions do this. Part of the reason I drifted from my faith was that I didn’t want to feel defensive about it. A pathetic reason, looking\n\nMay 19, 2015\n\u001c120\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cback, but true.\n\nMay 19, 2015\n\u001c120\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cMy worry was wasted. The Reb made no such value judgments. “Our faith tells us to do charitable acts and to aid the poor in our community,” he said. “That is being righteous, no matter who you help.”\n\nMay 19, 2015\n\u001c121\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cMay 19, 2015\n\u001c123\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\nThe Things We Find…\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cBut you can touch everything and be connected to nothing. I knew airports better than I knew local neighborhoods. I knew more names in other area codes than I did on my block. The “community” I had joined was the community of the workplace. Friends were through work. Conversation was about work. Most of my socialization came through work\n\nMay 19, 2015\n\u001c126\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cAnd in recent months, those workplace pillars had been falling down. Friends were laid off. Downsized. They took buyouts. Offices closed. People who were always in one place were no longer there when you called. They sent e-mails saying they were exploring “exciting new options.” I never believed the “exciting” part. And without the work connection, the human ties released,\n\nMay 20, 2015\n\u001c126\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cWe promised to keep up, but the promises were not kept. Some people behaved as if unemployment were contagious. Anyhow, without the commonality of work—the complaints, the gossip—how much was there to talk about?\n\nMay 20, 2015\n\u001c127\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\nWinter Solstice\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cBut there’s some people that know me from back when—anytime I make that trip to New York—and when they hear I’m the pastor of a church, all of a sudden, it’s like “I know you gettin’ paid, boy. I know you gettin’ paid. I know you.’” He paused. His voice lowered. “No, I say. You knew me. You knew that person, but you don’t know the person that I’m trying to become\n\nThey knew you. But they don\u0027t know the person you\u0027re trying to become\n\nMay 20, 2015\n\u001c146\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cYou are not your past!\n\nMirina, I also just want to work hard\n\nMay 20, 2015\n\u001c146\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\nGood and Evil\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cHe truly was happiest when he could help someone. But I assumed a Man of God had no choice. His religion obliged him toward what Lincoln called “the better angels of our nature.”\n\nMay 20, 2015\n\u001c148\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\nSaying Sorry\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cYou know what I found over the years? When I had a disagreement with someone, and they came to talk to me, I always began by saying, ‘I’ve thought about it. And in some ways maybe you’re right.’ “Now, I didn’t always believe that. But it made things easier. Right from the start, they relaxed. A negotiation could take place. I took a volatile situation and, what’s the word…?” Defused it? “Defused it. We need to do that. Especially with family. “You know, in our tradition, we\n\nMay 20, 2015\n\u001c159\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cask forgiveness from everyone—even casual acquaintances. But with those we are closest with—wives, children, parents—we too often let things linger. Don’t wait, Mitch. It’s such a waste.” He told me a story. A man buried his wife. At the gravesite he stood by the Reb, tears falling down his face. “I loved her,” he whispered. The Reb nodded. “I mean…I really loved her.” The man broke down. “And…I almost told her once.” The Reb looked at me sadly. “Nothing haunts like the things we don’t say.”\n\nTell coco u love her. And call dad. Make up with him and mom\n\nMay 20, 2015\n\u001c159\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cMay 20, 2015\n\u001c161\n\u0011\n\u0011\n\n\nThe Moment of Truth\n\n\u0010\u0012\u001c\n\u0010\u0012\u001c*\n\u001cBut I realized something as I drove home that night: that I am neither better nor smarter, only luckier. And I should be ashamed of thinking I knew everything, because you can know the whole world and still feel lost in it. So many people are in pain—no matter how smart or accomplished—they cry, they yearn, they hurt. But instead of looking down on things, they look up, which is where I should have been looking, too. Because when the world quiets to the sound of your own breathing, we all want the same things: comfort, love, and a peaceful heart.\n\nMay 21, 2015\n\u001c166\n\u0011\n\u0011"},{"ty":"te","id":"i.36","spi":8320},{"ty":"te","id":"i.37","spi":8696},{"ty":"te","id":"i.38","spi":8746},{"ty":"te","id":"i.39","spi":8980},{"ty":"te","id":"i.40","spi":9035},{"ty":"te","id":"i.41","spi":9409},{"ty":"te","id":"i.42","spi":9820},{"ty":"te","id":"i.43","spi":10085},{"ty":"te","id":"i.44","spi":10556},{"ty":"te","id":"i.45","spi":10668},{"ty":"te","id":"i.46","spi":10896},{"ty":"te","id":"i.47","spi":11409},{"ty":"te","id":"i.48","spi":12002},{"ty":"te","id":"i.49","spi":12057},{"ty":"as","st":"paragraph","si":8288,"ei":8288,"sm":{"ps_klt_i":true,"ps_sb_i":true,"ps_awao_i":true,"ps_ls":1.0,"ps_sa_i":true,"ps_sm_i":true,"ps_kwn_i":true,"ps_ifl_i":true,"ps_ls_i":true,"ps_il_i":true,"ps_ir_i":true,"ps_al_i":true}},{"ty":"as","st":"paragraph","si":8289,"ei":8289,"sm":{"ps_klt_i":true,"ps_sb_i":true,"ps_awao_i":true,"ps_ls":1.0,"ps_sa_i":true,"ps_sm_i":true,"ps_kwn_i":true,"ps_ifl_i":true,"ps_ls_i":true,"ps_